For the exploratory objective (PD) and outcome measures, see Section 3 of the protocol.
This is a multicentre, open-label study designed to evaluate the PK profile of tezepelumab following a single SC 70mg dose in children â‰¥5to11years of age with mild, moderate, or severe asthma.
The study will be conducted in 3to5 sites in the UnitedÂ Kingdom.

At least 12 paediatric subjects aged â‰¥5to11years (inclusive) will receive a single SC 70Â mg dose of tezepelumab. At least 4subjects will have body weight <25kg and a minimum of 3subjects will have body weight â‰¥25kgto<40kg. Approximately 24 subjects will be enrolled such that at least 12subjects complete the study.
The 99-day study consists of:
A consent/screening period of up to 14days
Treatment and follow-up period of 85days.
Subjects will be allocated to receive tezepelumab if they fulfil the eligibility criteria. This is an open-label non-randomised study.
Disclosure Statement : This is an open-label single arm study.
Approximately 24 subjects will be enrolled such that at least 12subjects complete the study.

Note : â€˜Enrolledâ€™ means a subjectâ€™s, and their legally acceptable representativeâ€™s agreement to participate in a clinical study following completion of the informed consent process. Potential subjects who are screened for the purpose of determining eligibility for the study but are not assigned in the study, are considered â€˜screen failuresâ€™, unless otherwise specified by the protocol.

The subjects will then return for Follow-up visits on DaysÂ 3, 7, 11, 15, 29, 57 and 85 (End of Study [EOS]). This is a 99-day study. Screening assessments should be completed within 14days (Day-14 to Day-1). The study will be completed after the EOS visit on Day85. Subjects who meet eligibility criteria will receive a single SC 70Â mg dose of tezepelumab on Day1.
No formal statistical hypothesis tests will be made. All data will be presented using descriptive statistics.

Additional PK parameters may be reported if appropriate. Individual tezepelumab serum concentration data will be tabulated along with descriptive statistics. AUC 0-inf /F). ss The following PK parameters will be estimated by noncompartmental analysis: area under the concentration-time curve (AUC) ), apparent clearance (CL/F) and apparent steady-state volume of distribution (V 1/2 ), terminal half-life (t max (t max ), time to C max maximum concentration (C 0-last

Safety will be assessed by summarising adverse events (AEs) and serious AEs (SAEs). Other variables used for the safety assessments include but are not limited to electrocardiograms (ECGs), vital signs and routine laboratory assessments. These variables as well as their changes from baseline will be summarised descriptively.
The incidence of positive serum antibodies to tezepelumab will be reported.
All PK summaries will be based on the PK analysis set. Anti-drug antibodies (ADA) and PD parameter summaries and safety presentations will be based on the safety analysis set.

A total of 12subjects treated with tezepelumab is considered sufficient to provide adequate data to characterise PK of tezepelumab in children â‰¥5 to 11 years of age. The number of subjects was based on the desire to obtain adequate PK and safety data while exposing as few paediatric subjects as possible to tezepelumab and study procedures. No formal sample size calculation was conducted for this study.

3.2 Exclusion Criteria
Subjects are excluded from the study if any of the following criteria apply:

1 History of any clinically significant disease or disorder other than asthma which, in the opinion of the Investigator, may either put the subject at risk because of participation in the study, or influence the results or the subjectâ€™s ability to participate in the study.
History of a deterioration in asthma or asthma exacerbation that required a burst of systemic corticosteroids within 3Â months of VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).

History of hospitalisation (overnight admission) for asthma within 6Â months of VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
History of a life-threatening asthma exacerbation requiring intubation or mechanical ventilation.
History of systemic corticosteroid use for the maintenance treatment of asthma within 3Â months of VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1) and discouraged until EOS.
A helminth parasitic infection diagnosed within 6Â months prior to VisitÂ 1 that has not been treated with, or has failed to respond to, standard of care therapy.

History of a clinically significant infection, including upper or lower respiratory tract infection (with or without treatment of antibiotics or systemic antivirals) within 2weeks of Visit 1 or during screening.
Tuberculosis requiring treatment within 12Â months prior to VisitÂ 1.
Any clinically significant illness, medical/surgical procedure, or trauma within 4Â weeks of VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
History of cancer.
Receipt of any marketed or investigational biologic agent within 4Â months or 5Â half-lives (whichever is longer) prior to VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
Receipt of any investigational non-biologic agent within 30Â days or 5Â half-lives (whichever is longer) prior to VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
Receipt of immunoglobin or blood products within 30Â days prior to VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
Receipt of live attenuated vaccines 30Â days prior to VisitÂ 1, up to and including VisitÂ 2 (DayÂ 1).
Subjects with known hypersensitivity to tezepelumab or any excipients of the product.
History of hypersensitivity or anaphylactic reaction to any biologic therapy.
Concurrent enrolment in another drug-related interventional clinical trial.

Any clinically relevant abnormal findings in physical examination, ECG, vital signs, haematology, clinical chemistry, or urinalysis during screening, which in the opinion of the Investigator, may put the subject at risk because of his/her participation in the study, or may influence the results of the study, or the subjectâ€™s ability to complete entire duration of the study.

Evidence of active liver disease, including jaundice or aspartate aminotransferase (AST), alanine aminotransferase (ALT), or alkaline phosphatase (ALP) >2 Ã— the upper limit of normal (ULN) at VisitÂ 1. Positive hepatitis B surface antigen or hepatitis C virus antibody serology at Visit 1, or a positive medical history for hepatitis B or C. Subjects with a history of hepatitisB vaccination without history of hepatitis B are allowed to enrol.

Previous enrolment in the present study.
Lifestyle Considerations
3.3.1 Meals and Dietary Restrictions
Subjects should avoid eating a large meal for at least 2 hours prior to all lung function assessments at the centre.
Subjects should not eat or drink one hour prior to having the FENO test.
Activity
Subjects should avoid engaging in strenuous exertion for at least 30 minutes prior to all lung function assessments at the centre.
Screen Failures

Minimal information includes demography, screen failure details, eligibility criteria and any SAE. Screen failures are defined as subjects who signed the ICF to participate in the clinical study but are not subsequently assigned to study treatment. A minimal set of screen failure information is required to ensure transparent reporting of screen failure subjects to meet the Consolidated Standards of Reporting Trials (CONSORT) publishing requirements and to respond to queries from regulatory authorities.

Individuals who do not meet the criteria for participation in this study (screen failure) may be rescreened. ], or other transient conditions). Rescreened subjects should be assigned the same subject number as for the initial screening and be re-consented. 5.2 Only one rescreen attempt is allowed in the study and only if the reason for screen failure was transient (including but not limited to equipment failure, exclusion criterion#8 [Section

Rescreening should be discussed with the CRO Medical Monitor. Subjects rescreened more than 30 days after initial screening must repeat all assessments and meet all entry criteria noted in the protocol. If rescreening is performed within 30 days of initial screening, assessments from initial screening may be used, however clinically significant findings must be reassessed, and the subject must meet all entry criteria noted in the protocol.
